FRED Tutorial

6/13/2021

How to use FRED dataset in R

Load library

Load libraries for accessing FRED website, manipulating data, and visualizing output.

library(fredr)
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)

To download data from FRED website, we need to create an account first, then acquire an API key for accessing FRED API. The API key must be set using fredr_set_key() function before using fredr function.

fredr_set_key("YOUR_API_KEY")

Single series

Import data into R directly

fredr function retrieve data specified in series_id, convert them into table-like format.

dataset <- fredr(
  series_id = "UNRATE",
  observation_start = as.Date("1990-01-01"),
  observation_end = as.Date("2000-01-01")
)

Inspect data

The data consist of 5 columns and 121 observations.

str(dataset)

##  $ date          : Date[1:121], format: "1990-01-01" "1990-02-01" ...

The column value indicates unemployment rate. Let’s calculate n, max, min, mean, and median of unemployment rate.

dataset %>% summarize(n=n(), max=max(value), min=min(value), mean = mean(value), median=median(value))
## # A tibble: 1 x 5
##       n   max   min  mean median
##   <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1   121   7.8     4  5.75    5.6

Plot data

Let’s draw line chart of unemployment rate using ggplot package.

dataset %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=date,y=value)) +
  labs(title="Unemployment rate in USA", x="Year",y="%") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "year" , date_labels = "%Y") +
  geom_line()

Multiple serieses

Import data

In this case, we import multiple series: unemployment rate and job openings.

dataset <- map_dfr(c("UNRATE", "JTSJOL"), fredr)

For visualization, we modify table into wider format, where each series become a separte column.

dataset_wider <- dataset %>%
  select(date,series_id,value) %>% pivot_wider(names_from="series_id", values_from="value")
dataset_wider
## # A tibble: 881 x 3

Plot data

dataset_wider %>% 
  drop_na() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=date)) +
  geom_line( aes(y=UNRATE), color="red") + # Divide by 10 to get the same range than the temperature
  geom_line( aes(y=JTSJOL/1000), color="blue") + 
  scale_y_continuous(
    name = "Unemployment rate",
    sec.axis = sec_axis(~.*1000,name="Job openings")) +
  theme(axis.title.y.left = element_text(colour = "red"),
        axis.title.y.right = element_text(colour = "blue"))
